definition.value: A sulfur hydride consisting of a single sulfur atom bonded to two hydrogen atoms. A highly poisonous, flammable gas with a characteristic odour of rotten eggs, it is often produced by bacterial decomposition of organic matter in the absence of oxygen.
A mucopolysaccharide composed of repeating beta-D-glucopyranuronosyl-(1->3)-beta-D-N-acetylgalactosaminyl units.
A trivalent inorganic anion obtained by removal of all three protons from selenophosphoric acid.
A straight-chain alkane with 17 carbon atoms. It is a component of essential oils from plants like Opuntia littoralis and Annona squamosa.
The simplest member of the class of  benzoates that is the conjugate base of benzoic acid, comprising a benzoic acid core with a proton missing to give a charge of -1.
A dihydroxybenzoate that is the  conjugate base of o-orsellinic acid.
An L-cysteine thioether that is L-cysteine in which the hydrogen of the thiol group has been replaced by a carboxymethyl group.
A  benzenetriol carrying hydroxy groups at positions 1, 2 and 3.
A gluconolactone derived form  D-gluconic acid.
A synthetic monocyclic beta-lactam antibiotic (monobactam).
The D-enantiomer of ornithine. It is an intermediate metabolite produced in the urea cycle.
An N-acyl-amino acid in which amino acid specified is glycine.
A one-carbon compound in which the carbon is attached by single bonds to four hydrogen atoms. It is a colourless, odourless, non-toxic but flammable gas (b.p. -161degreeC).
A sulfur oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of both OH groups of sulfuric acid.
A monohydroxybenzoate that is the conjugate base of 3-hydroxybenzoic acid.
An octadec-9-enoic acid in which the double bond at C-9 has Z (cis) stereochemistry.
A carbonyl group with two C-bound amine groups.
A benzenetriol with hydroxy groups at position 1, 3 and 5.
A hydroxybenzaldehyde carrying a hydroxy substituent at position 3.
A divalent inorganic anion obtained by removal of both protons from phosphonic acid
An  aldono-1,5-lactone obtained from D-gluconic acid.
The beta-anomer of D-glucose 1-phosphate.
An optically active glycerol 1-phosphate having (S)-configuration.
Any N-acyl-L-alpha-amino acid that is L-lysine in which the N(6) amino group has been acylated.
A 2-aminopurine carrying a 6-oxo substituent.
A primary alcohol that is ethane in which one of the hydrogens is substituted by a hydroxy group.
A flavin adenine dinucleotide in which the substituent at position 10 of the flavin nucleus is a 5'-adenosyldiphosphoribityl group.
An inorganic peroxide consisting of two hydroxy groups joined by a covalent oxygen-oxygen single bond.
An amino-acid betaine gamma-aminobutyric acid zwitterion in which all of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogen are replaced by methyl groups.
A lipid containing phosphoric acid as a mono- or di-ester. The term encompasses phosphatidic acids and phosphoglycerides.
A member of the class of 2-nitrophenols that is phenol in which one of the hydrogens that is ortho to the hydroxy group has been replaced by a nitro group.
An aminoglycan consisting of beta-(1->4)-linked D-glucosamine residues.
The L-enantiomer of the sulfur-containing amino acid cystine.
A branched-chain saturated fatty acid consisting of hexadecanoic acid carrying methyl substituents at positions 3, 7, 11 and 15.
The D-enantiomer of tryptophan.
The nitrogen oxoanion formed by loss of a proton from nitrous acid.
A cobalamin in which the central cobalt atom has an oxidation state of +2.
The D-enantiomer of proline.
A member of the class of catechols that is benzene-1,2-diol substituted by a nitro group at position 4.It is the by-product of the hydroxylation of p-nitrophenol.
A glutamic semialdehyde that is L-glutamate 5-semialdehyde in which one of the hydrogens of the amino group has been replaced by an acetyl group.
A ribonucleoside composed of a molecule of adenine attached to a ribofuranose moiety via a beta-N(9)-glycosidic bond.
A mucopolysaccharide composed of N-acetylglucosamine and glucuronic acid subunits. It is found in the connective tissues of vertebrates.
A derivative of glycerol in which one hydroxy group, commonly but not necessarily primary, is esterified with phosphoric acid and the other two are esterified with fatty acids.
